  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Helps track and prevent money laundering\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n- Allowed prosecution of individuals involved in financial transactions with proceeds from illegal activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Expanded anti-money laundering provisions\n- Enhanced government's ability to track and prevent money laundering\n- Increased reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Strengthened collaboration between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Most recent major legislation addressing money laundering\n- Modernized and expanded existing anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n- Improved transparency and reporting requirements\n\nThese statutes work together to provide a comprehensive legal framework for detecting, preventing, and prosecuting money laundering activities in the United States.",
